it. Far away voices demanding her attention, among other things. She had found she couldn't enjoy things the way she used to.<br>
These were her dark thoughts when she ran into Kandiya, returning from Tradeskilling in the Plane of Knowledge. <br>
&quot;...Kaly, hellooooo...are you there?&quot;<br>
&quot;I'm sorry Kandi, were you calling me?&quot;<br>
&quot;I was, but only curious why you're here and not out hunting, or your usual tradeskilling. Something wrong?&quot; Kandi asked. &quot;Perhaps so,&quot; Kaly conceded.<br>
&quot;I find I have no interest in things as I used to. I'm not sure what to do. It's got me a little depressed to be honest. I've always enjoyed every little thing. And now it's all...I don't know.&quot; She smiled at her friend. Kaly had known Kandi since she had put in her application to Claw, and had found a fast friendship. She enjoyed teasing the darkelf, particularly tugging on her long snow-white hair. (Kaly was secretly envious that Kandi had such beautiful hair, but was too attached to her coloring to change it in any way....but then Kandi didn't have to know THAT.) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I'd never live it down!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She thought.<br>
&quot;I'm glad I ran into you. I've been doing some thinking lately, though you may not like what I have to say I'm afraid I don't see an alternative. Will you come with me back to my rooms?&quot;<br>
Kandiya frowned at Kaly's serious tone. This wasn't like the Kaly she knew. Kandiya decided to follow Kaly and listen to what she had to say.<br>
<br>
When the two were settled, Kaly explained how she'd been feeling to Kandiya, certain that her friend would understand. &quot;I&quot;m sorry Kandi. I want to stay but I don't think I can anymore. I was wondering if you would take care of my things for me. I don't believe I can take them where I'm going. Not quite sure where that is going to be yet, but I need to find my way again.&quot; Kaly wiped the tears from her eyes. &quot;I want to stay, but I don't feel like I'm advancing anymore. I'm not going anywhere and I don't like the feeling.&quot;<br>
Kandiya hugged the druid close. &quot;It's okay, Kaly, really. Have no worry about your things, they'll be well taken care of.&quot;<br>
&quot;I knew I could count on you, my friend. I appreciate it immensely. I don't know how I can repay you...&quot; Kaly said.<br>
&quot;Think nothing of it!&quot; Kandiya exclaimed. &quot;And the only thing I want in return is for you to come back to us someday.&quot;<br>
Kalyndria grinned through her tears. She knew she could count on Kandi to help. &quot;I'll come back. I just need to go my own way for a while. Thanks, hon, for everything.&quot; Kaly hugged her friend, and tugged on her hair.<br>
&quot;Ow! Why you..&quot; Kandiya grinned. Still the same ol' Kaly. <br>
With everything taken care of, her place assured to stay, Kaly felt as if a great weight had been taken off her shoulders. She bid her friend farewell, and took a last longing look around her quarters in the Claw of Nagafen's Guildhall. Then, casting a spell, she raised her arms above her head, and faded away.<br>
